{"parse":{"title":"Lord Hay's Masque","pageid":10191939,"revid":854475749,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>\n\n<i><b>Lord Hay's Masque</b></i> was an early <a href=\"/wiki/Literature_in_English#Jacobean_literature\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Literature in English\">Jacobean</a> era <a href=\"/wiki/Masque\" title=\"Masque\">masque</a>, written by <a href=\"/wiki/Thomas_Campion\" title=\"Thomas Campion\">Thomas Campion</a>, with costumes, sets and stage effects designed by <a href=\"/wiki/Inigo_Jones\" title=\"Inigo Jones\">Inigo Jones</a>. The masque was performed on <a href=\"/wiki/Twelfth_Night_(holiday)\" title=\"Twelfth Night (holiday)\">Twelfth Night</a>, 6 January <a href=\"/wiki/1607_in_literature\" title=\"1607 in literature\">1607</a>, in the Great Hall of <a href=\"/wiki/Whitehall_Palace\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Whitehall Palace\">Whitehall Palace</a>. It was the premier event at the <a href=\"/wiki/House_of_Stuart\" title=\"House of Stuart\">Stuart</a> Court for the 1606-7 Christmas holiday season.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#The_marriage\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">The marriage</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#The_masque\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">The masque</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#The_music\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">The music</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Publication\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Publication</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#Aftermath\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Aftermath</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#See_Also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See Also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-7\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">7</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-8\"><a href=\"#Sources\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">8</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Sources</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"The_marriage\">The marriage</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Lord_Hay%27s_Masque&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: The marriage\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><i>Lord Hay's Masque</i> celebrated the wedding of an important Scottish aristocrat with a socially prominent English <a href=\"/wiki/Gentlewoman\" title=\"Gentlewoman\">gentlewoman</a> &#8212; in this case, the marriage of <a href=\"/wiki/James_Hay,_1st_Earl_of_Carlisle\" title=\"James Hay, 1st Earl of Carlisle\">Sir James Hay</a>, a favorite of King <a href=\"/wiki/James_I_of_England\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"James I of England\">James I</a> (and one of the masquers in <i>Hymenaei</i> the previous year), with Honoria Denny, daughter of <a href=\"/wiki/Edward_Denny,_1st_Earl_of_Norwich\" title=\"Edward Denny, 1st Earl of Norwich\">Edward, Lord Denny</a>. The intricate politics of the Stuart Court decreed some key differences between the two events, though: while the bill for the previous masque, <i>Hymenaei</i>, had been paid by King James, the expenses of the masque for Lord Hay were covered by the powerful Howard and <a href=\"/wiki/Robert_Cecil,_1st_Earl_of_Salisbury\" title=\"Robert Cecil, 1st Earl of Salisbury\">Cecil</a> families. The principal masquers were led by Theophilus Howard, Lord Walden, the son and heir of the Earl of Suffolk. Since James's queen consort, <a href=\"/wiki/Anne_of_Denmark\" title=\"Anne of Denmark\">Anne of Denmark</a>, was antipathetic to the Howards, she sat out the masque, claiming illness.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> (Partially as a result, the documentary record on <i>Lord Hay's Masque</i> is thinner than for some other Court masques of the era.)\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"The_masque\">The masque</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Lord_Hay%27s_Masque&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: The masque\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Jones's design for the masque had a sylvan theme, centered on a Grove of <a href=\"/wiki/Diana_(mythology)\" title=\"Diana (mythology)\">Diana</a> with nine golden trees, flanked by a Bower of <a href=\"/wiki/Flora_(mythology)\" title=\"Flora (mythology)\">Flora</a> on the right and a House of Night on the left. One scene featured artificial owls and bats flying around the set on wires. The nine gold trees moved and danced and split apart to reveal the nine principal masquers (the trees then sank into the stage below, at a touch from Night's wand). The masquers, dressed in carnation and cloth of silver and initially concealed in green and silver leaves, were nine knights of <a href=\"/wiki/Apollo\" title=\"Apollo\">Apollo</a>, and the torchbearers were the nine Hours of the night.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"The_music\">The music</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Lord_Hay%27s_Masque&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: The music\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The masque was richly supplied with music, created by several composers &#8212; including Campion himself, who contributed two \"airs\" for songs and a dance. The published text indicates that the music was played by a \"consort of twelve,\" violins with three lutes, a \"consort of ten\" that included <a href=\"/wiki/Harpsichord\" title=\"Harpsichord\">harpsichord</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Bandora_(instrument)\" title=\"Bandora (instrument)\">bandora</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Sackbut\" title=\"Sackbut\">sackbut</a>, and two violins as well as lutes, and a group of <a href=\"/wiki/Cornet\" title=\"Cornet\">cornets</a>. A few details of the musical arrangements have survived, including the fact that at least one song was sung by a doubled set of voices, with a treble and bass situated near the King and another set of singers on the stage, \"so that the words of the song might be heard of all.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Publication\">Publication</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Lord_Hay%27s_Masque&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Publication\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Campion's text was entered into the <a href=\"/wiki/Stationers%27_Register\" title=\"Stationers&#39; Register\">Stationers' Register</a> on 26 January 1607 and was published in <a href=\"/wiki/Book_size\" title=\"Book size\">quarto</a> shortly after, printed by John Windet for the bookseller John Browne.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Campion's verses conjoin the personal and political, hailing the marriage of Hay and Denny and looking forward to a day when English/Scottish intermarriage will produce a new \"British\" citizen.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Aftermath\">Aftermath</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Lord_Hay%27s_Masque&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: Aftermath\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Such political and social import is a heavy load to lay on a new marriage. Within two years the couple were facing difficulties. Honoria was supposedly unfaithful and Hay was jealous; he broke open her cabinets in search of love letters and threatened her servants. Lady <a href=\"/wiki/Mary_Wroth\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mary Wroth\">Mary Wroth</a> exploited their troubles in <i>Urania,</i> her prose <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_%C3%A0_clef\" title=\"Roman \u00e0 clef\">roman \u00e0 clef</a> about Stuart high society.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_Also\">See Also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Lord_Hay%27s_Masque&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: See Also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Lords%27s_Masque&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"The Lords&#39;s Masque (page does not exist)\"> The Lords' Masque</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Lord_Hay%27s_Masque&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Barroll, pp. 109. 203.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Chambers, Vol. 3, p. 241; Leapman, p. 93.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Walls, p. 43.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Chambers, Vol. 3, p. 240.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Cerasano and Wynne-Davies, pp. 93-4.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Sources\">Sources</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Lord_Hay%27s_Masque&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8\" title=\"Edit section: Sources\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>Barroll, John Leeds. <i>Anna of Denmark, Queen of England: A Cultural Biography.</i> Philadelphia, University of Pennsylvania Press, 2001.</li>\n<li>Cerasano, S. P., and Marion Wynne-Davies. <i>Gloriana's Face: Women, Public and Private, in the English Renaissance.</i> Detroit, Wayne State University Press, 1992.</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Edmund_Kerchever_Chambers\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Edmund Kerchever Chambers\">Chambers, E. K.</a> <i>The Elizabethan Stage.</i> 4 Volumes, Oxford, Clarendon Press, 1923.</li>\n<li>Leapman, Michael. <i>Inigo: The Troubled Life of Inigo Jones, Architect of the English Renaissance.</i> London, Headline Book Publishing, 2003.</li>\n<li>Lindley, David. <i>Thomas Campion.</i> Leiden, Brill Academic Publishers, 1986.</li>\n<li>Walls, Peter. <i>Music in the English Courtly Masque, 1604&#8211;1640.</i> Oxford, Clarendon Press, 1996.</li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1268\nCached time: 20180903230607\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.072 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.092 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 341/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 1463/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 341/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 12/40\nExpensive parser function count: 2/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 1304/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.014/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 820 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   71.298      1 -total\n 40.01%   28.523      1 Template:Italic_title\n 28.54%   20.348      1 Template:Use_dmy_dates\n 24.87%   17.729      2 Template:DMCA\n 22.05%   15.724      2 Template:Dated_maintenance_category\n 16.32%   11.639      1 Template:Reflist\n 14.57%   10.390      2 Template:FULLROOTPAGENAME\n  8.92%    6.361      2 Template:Ns_has_subpages\n  8.45%    6.024      1 Template:Use_British_English\n  3.03%    2.161      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:10191939-0!canonical and timestamp 20180903230607 and revision id 854475749\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","hidden":"","*":"Use_dmy_dates_from_November_2012"},{"sortkey":"","hidden":"","*":"Use_British_English_from_November_2012"},{"sortkey":"","*":"English_Renaissance_plays"},{"sortkey":"","*":"1607_plays"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Masques"}],"links":[{"ns":14,"exists":"","*":"Category:Use dmy dates from November 2012"},{"ns":14,"exists":"","*":"Category:Use British English from November 2012"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"1607 in literature"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Anne of Denmark"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Apollo"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Bandora (instrument)"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Book size"},{"ns":0,"exi